**Three Traits of a Good Salesman**

It’s somewhat of a standing joke that people dislike salesmen. From workplace grumbling to sitcom ridicule, salesmen get a bad rap.

“Nobody likes salesmen,” we shrug, as if it’s the natural way of the world.

But I think it’s better phrased that “Nobody likes *bad* salesmen.”

Sales are a critical part of business: there’s no way around it. But is it necessary that salesmen be annoying, greedy, and generally unlikeable?

Absolutely not. These are signs of a *bad* salesman.

Good salesmen are very likeable--but you probably don’t think of them as salesmen.

So what makes good salesmen? How do they act? How do they come through? And more importantly, how can we businesspeople become good salesmen?

Today I am sharing with you a few traits I’ve learned every good salesman possesses. I hope you find them helpful.

**Three Traits of a Good Salesman**

***1\. Good salesmen are honest.*** 

The first and greatest trait of good salesmen is honesty. Customers are experts at sensing deception or manipulation and they will run away once they smell it. 

Be honest about whether or not your product or service is the best fit for your client--don’t undersell it, but be honest. This will endear customers to your business and demonstrate your trustworthiness.

***2\. Good salesmen are genuinely helpful.***

Here’s solid truth: the dogged pursuit of money will leave you empty. True fulfillment comes only through genuinely serving others. Give your life both professionally and personally to serving others from a sincere heart.

Do your best to genuinely meet the needs of your customers. They are the hero, you are the servant and guide.

Figure out what your customer wants and give it to them.

***3\. Good salesmen relieve the pressure to buy.***

Customers come to your business because they need help. They don’t come to make you rich.

Pressuring them to buy your product will only turn them off, not only from the purchase, but from your business as a whole. Be honest with how you can help them and how you cannot, letting them lead the sales process.

Although this flies in the face of “conventional sales wisdom”, it is the only way to build long-lasting relationships with your customers. Your willingness to take the time to build a long-term relationship will prove to them you are genuine and not selling out of selfish motives.

***BONUS TRAIT: Good salesmen are concise.***

We’ve all experienced a painful example of time-wasting salesmanship, such as:

1. Door-to-door salesmen who shove their way into a sweet grandma’s living room to give a demonstration  
2. Realtors who drag their buyers from house-to-house, increasing the pressure to buy  
3. Telemarketers who call during dinner and refuse to take no for an answer

Being concise is one of the finest skills you can acquire, whether as a writer, speaker, salesperson, or just as a regular joe.

What you have to say is important: Don’t hide it in a long mess of sentences\! Just stand up, speak up, and shut up. Remember: concise is nice.

*What other important traits have you seen? What are ways you can change in your selling? Share your insight in the comments below\!*
